{
  "texts": [
    "Definition 2.1.",
    "The Q-module 𝐴 Q (C) is called a (rational) abstract Burnside ring if the Burnside homomorphism is an injective Q-module map.",
    "If the Burnside homomorphism 𝜙: 𝐴 Q (C) → Q C is injective, then it is an isomorphism since domain and codomain are Q-vector spaces of the same dimension.",
    "As such, there is a unique ring structure on 𝐴 Q (C) such that the Burnside homomorphism is a ring map.",
    "By construction, the Burnside homomorphism is represented by the hom-set |C| × |C|-matrix 𝐻 given by 𝐻 𝑐𝑑 = |C(𝑐, 𝑑)|."
  ]
}